BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:TX-MNdADECLxvJ4F6Kg5h
SUMMARY:TADAIMA: I'm Home
DTSTAMP:20260307T213102Z
DTSTART:20260311T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:After more than 80 years\, a treasured collection returns “home
	” to Seattle’s Japanese American community. In 1942 dozens of traditional 
	Boys’ and Girls’ Day dolls were entrusted to Bailey Gatzert Elementary Sch
	ool by Japanese American families facing forced incarceration. Most were n
	ever reclaimed after the war. Artist Miya Sukune uses recent research in M
	OHAI’s collection\, as well as interviews with Japanese American survivors
	 and their descendants\, to create an installation called “Tadaima\,” mean
	ing “I’m home.”\n\nTADAIMA: “I’m Home!” Bringing Seattle’s Girls’ and Boys
	’ Day Dolls Home reconnects the dolls with their traditional role of prote
	cting and blessing children. It invites visitors to celebrate the resilien
	ce\, memory\, and enduring traditions of the Japanese American Community.\
	n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/tadaima-i-m-home/18096356
	/2026-03-11T00
LOCATION:Museum of History and Industry\, 860 Terry Ave N\, Seattle\, Seatt
	le\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:U7J7YV--NXBdo81StVFyM
SUMMARY:Get Grant Ready
DTSTAMP:20260307T213102Z
DTSTART:20260311T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Description    Get Grant Ready: Grants Preparedness Workshop fo
	r Micro Businesses Join GSBA for a practical Spring workshop focused on he
	lping small and micro businesses break down barriers to securing grants. A
	bout This Workshop Facilitated by GSBA's Grant Writer & Manager\, Devonshi
	re Lokke\, this Spring workshop will focus on breaking down barriers to se
	curing grants for small and micro business. Topics will include grant rese
	arch \\(where to find grants for small businesses\\)\, grant writing \\(ho
	w to apply for grants\\)\, budgeting \\(how to track and manage grant fund
	s\\)\, and reporting \\(how to share successes and challenges with funders
	\\). As a grant writer and manager for 6\\+ years\, Devonshire knows that 
	grants can seem intimidating and overwhelming\, especially for a small or 
	micro-business owner. This workshop will provide entrepreneurs with the co
	nfidence\, tools\, and resources to quickly and competitively pursue futur
	e grant opportunities \\(presented by both GSBA and other funders\\). Work
	shops will be open to GSBA members and non-members and will be in person a
	t the GSBA offices in Capitol Hill\, Seattle. The session will conclude wi
	th 30 minutes of Q&A\, to address participants' unique business needs. Wha
	t You'll Learn Where to find grant opportunities relevant to small and mic
	ro businesses How to read and assess grant requirements before applying Be
	st practices for grant applications and narratives How to build and track 
	grant budgets with confidence What funders expect in grant reporting and f
	ollow-up Common pitfalls-and how to avoid them Who Should Attend Micro bus
	inesses and sole proprietors Early-stage entrepreneurs Businesses applying
	 for grants for the first time Businesses that have applied before but wan
	t stronger results Business owners seeking clear\, practical guidance No p
	rior grant experience is required.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/
	#/details/get-grant-ready/18089677/2026-03-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Ev
	ents
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/get-grant-ready/18089677/
	2026-03-11T00
LOCATION:GSBA\, 400 E Pine St Ste 322\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H30M
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:PMJF82GUC0w2VY4VM7Yhh
SUMMARY:Samantha Yun Wall: What We Leave Behind
DTSTAMP:20260307T213102Z
DTSTART:20260311T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Samantha Yun Wall’s new paintings use overlapping silhouettes o
	f female figures as portals to unknown spaces and different temporal realm
	s. Impetus for the new body of work is a Korean folk tale in which the Pas
	que flower is symbolic of a grandmother who passed away without the loving
	 care of her grandchildren. It is a story of melancholy\, loss\, and remem
	brance. The delicate hair on the flower’s stem differentiates it\, and the
	 artist gives the plant a surreal aspect in some of her paintings\, replac
	ing the flower’s center with a watchful eye.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we-leave-behind/18026187/2026-0
	3-11T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/samantha-yun-wall-what-we
	-leave-behind/18026187/2026-03-11T00
LOCATION:Seattle Art Museum\, 1300 First Avenue\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT7H
END:VEVENT
