BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eX4W2qgoGAjn4IJUd_rNA
SUMMARY:Introduction to Orchid Care and Repotting
DTSTAMP:20260307T213103Z
DTSTART:20260314T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:Introduction to Orchids and their care. The orchid family \\(Or
	chidacea\\) is one of the largest and most diverse plant families. It poss
	ibly represents 10% of the flowering plant species. There are between 20\,
	000 and 35\,000 species \\(about 800 genera\\) and can be found on every c
	ontinent except Antarctica. There are 41 native terrestrial orchid species
	 in Washington State. Orchids are characterized by having highly specializ
	ed flower adaptations usually for pollination by insects. This class will 
	cover the physical characteristics of orchids\, care and feeding of the pl
	ants. Each student is encourages to bring up to 3 of their plants for eval
	uation and possible repotting. The lecture and demonstration portion of th
	e class will be one hour followed by the evaluation and repotting demonstr
	ations for an hour.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/intro
	duction-to-orchid-care-and-repotting/18295183/2026-03-14T00\n\nFrom SEAtod
	ay - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/introduction-to-orchid-ca
	re-and-repotting/18295183/2026-03-14T00
LOCATION:Volunteer Park Conservatory\, 1400 East Galer Street\, Seattle\, W
	A
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
