BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:dIeCbUZoK1ZXwb8XlSsi3
SUMMARY:La Cocina Cooking Class con Chef Garzón (Bad Chancla)
DTSTAMP:20260307T213103Z
DTSTART:20260315T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:La Cocina Cooking Class con Chef Garzón \\(Bad Chancla\\)\n\nSu
	nday\, March 15\, 2026\n\nTurn pantry staples into comfort food with heart
	. Join us on March 15th from 12:00 pm to 2:00 pm for a hands-on cooking cl
	ass with Bad Chancla\, where you’ll learn how to make white rice\, guisada
	 beans\, savory picadillo ground beef\, and a bright salsa criolla using e
	veryday ingredients.\n\nThis class will also cover quick pickling\, hybrid
	 cooking \\(using both canned and fresh vegetables\\)\, and smart ways to 
	stretch and elevate your pantry essentials\, no fancy tools or ingredients
	 required\; just an apron if you have one! We will provide all the ingredi
	ents and there will be time at the end of the class to enjoy the delicious
	 meal we create.\n\nAll proceeds support our Senior Program\, which provid
	es healthy meals\, a welcoming space\, and social activities for elders Mo
	nday through Friday. Come cook\, learn practical skills\, and give back to
	 our community\, all in one delicious night!\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.c
	om/events/#/details/la-cocina-cooking-class-con-chef-garz-n-bad-chancla/18
	206806/2026-03-15T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/la-cocina-cooking-class-c
	on-chef-garz-n-bad-chancla/18206806/2026-03-15T00
LOCATION:El Centro De La Raza\, 2524 16th Ave S\, Seattle\, WA
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:RpanwSjWFAdaAqoEgxBH8
SUMMARY:Susan Meiselas: Crossings
DTSTAMP:20260307T213103Z
DTSTART:20260315T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:First presented at the Art Institute of Chicago in 1990\, this 
	exhibition by Susan Meiselas intertwines documentary photographs of Centra
	l America during the 1970s and 1980s \\(from Nicaragua and El Salvador\\) 
	along with panoramic images from the US/Mexico border taken in 1989. Addit
	ional photographs of the US/Mexico border taken in 2018 are also featured 
	in a site-specific gallery installation. The exhibition invites viewers to
	 see immigration in the context of economic and political crises in the re
	gion.\n\nToday\, the work feels newly urgent. US immigration enforcement h
	as expanded through militarization and constant surveillance\, with leader
	s using fear-driven language to divide communities and legitimize brutal f
	orms of control.\n\nThese photographs ask us to look carefully\, to recogn
	ize familiar patterns\, and to hold on to our shared humanity across the g
	lobe. People move in search of safety\, possibility\, and a better life fo
	r their families\, which is a universal hope that crosses borders\, genera
	tions\, and time.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/susan-m
	eiselas-crossings/17977024/2026-03-15T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/susan-meiselas-crossings/
	17977024/2026-03-15T00
LOCATION:Photographic Center Northwest (PCNW)\, 900 12th Ave.\, Seattle\, W
	A
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT6H
END:VEVENT
